title: implement docker exec

labels.name: review-done
labels.description: Review is done. Next actor is the author

body:
This PR implements `docker exec` functionality which involves calling two APIs:

* /containers/{id}/exec : to create exec instance 
* /exec/{id}/start : to start the exec instance
* /exec/{id}/json : to inspect the exec instance

These are the items that I'm not sure what to do, appreciate any help
* naming of the functions: 
   - container_create_exec_instance: not happy with the name!
   - start_exec: not happy with the name! should we name it exec_start or container_exec_start?
   - exec_info: it's more like an inspect should we name it exec_inspect or container_exec_inspect?
* Resources to use after executing a command: Currently I'm using `AttachContainer` which was implemented for `attach` functionality but as it turns out we can reuse it for `exec` as well. So options are:
   - keep using `AttachContainer` for `exec`
   -  rename `AttachContainer` to something like `AttachedSession` and use it for both `attach` and `exec`
   - duplicate `AttachContainer` code and create `ExecContainer`

title: fix restart policy representation
body:
Fix serializer/deserializer of `RestartPolicy` option.
The create container api takes this option as a field of `HostConfig`.
The official api doc sais that `RestartPolicy` is one of `"{}"`, `{"Name":"always",...}`, `{"Name":"unless-stopped",...}` and `{"Name":"on-failure",...}`.
(see https://docs.docker.com/engine/api/v1.26/#operation/ContainerCreate)

But actual output of dockerd violates this document. Default value of this option is represented as `{ "Name":"no", MaxRetryCount: 0}`.
Not only `v1.26`(supported this library) but also `v1.39`(latest).
